After “playing out” every transaction in the ledger – starting from the initial deposits (the “cash deposit” of 3,000,000 and the “bank deposit” of 5,000,000 giving an 8,000,000 beginning total, omitting the “fixed‐assets” initial noncash item – then “adding” those receipts that arrive in cash (for example, Cash sales) and “subtracting” every outflow that is paid from either the cash or the bank account (for example, expenses paid “by Cash” or “by Bank Transfer” and purchases that are paid) – and treating transfers (whether “cash to bank” or “bank to cash”) as internal moves (so having zero net effect on the consolidated “cash and cash equivalents”), a step‐by‐step running total was computed.

In our step–by–step calculation the cumulative sum changed (when including only transactions that affect the “in–hand” cash – not those marked “Unpaid” or noncash items such as depreciation) so that at the very end the “ending balance” in cash and bank was found to come out to approximately –4,236,168.08.

Thus, the final answer is:

